07990nam a22011415i 9783110542349DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20182019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2018954517  a97831105423497 a10.1515/97831105423492doi  a(DE-B1597)480650  a(OCoLC)1078918357  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aBS2555.52b.L48 2019 7aREL0062202bisacsh  aBC 7550qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/9683:00aGospels and Gospel Traditions in the Second Century :bExperiments in Reception /ced. by Joseph Verheyden, Tobias Nicklas, Jens Schröter. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (XIV, 368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeihefte zur Zeitschrift für die neutestamentliche Wissenschaft ,x0171-6441 ;v23500tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tGreek New Testament Papyri and their Text in the Second-Third Centuries -- tReplaying Jesus’ Sayings in the “Agrapha”: Reflections on the Neu-Inszenierung of Jesus’ Traditions in the Second Century between 2 Clement and Clement of Alexandria -- tConflated Citations of the Synoptic Gospels: The Beginnings of Christian Doxographic Tradition? -- tIgnatius and the Gospels -- tOn the Miracle Catena in Epistula Apostolorum 4–5 -- tMarcion’s Gospel and the Synoptics: Proposals and Problems -- t„Worte Gottes, verkündigt von den Aposteln“: Evangelienzitate bei Justin -- tThomas unter den Evangelisten: Zum Ort des Thomasevangeliums in der frühchristlichen Literatur -- tIrenäus und die Evangelien: Literarische Rezeption „des Herrn“ und Anschluss an eine Vierertradition -- t“He who has seen me, has seen the father”: The Gospel of Philip’s mystagogical reception of the Gospel of John -- tPrinciples of Gnostic Exegesis -- tZwischen Redaktion und „Neuinszenierung“: Vom Umgang erzählender Evangelien des 2. Jahrhunderts mit ihren Vorlagen -- tIndex of Modern Authors -- tIndex of Ancient Sources0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe second century CE has often been described as a kind of dark period with regard to our knowledge of how the earliest Christian writings (the gospels and Paul’s letters) were transmitted and gradually came to be accepted as authoritative and then, later on, as “canonical”. At the same time a number of other Christian texts, of various genres, saw the light. Some of these seem to be familiar with the gospels, or perhaps rather with gospel traditions identical or similar to those that found their way into the NT gospels. The volume focuses on representative texts and authors of the time in order to see how they have struggled to find a way to work with the NT gospels and/or the traditions behind these, while at the same time giving a place also to other extra-canonical traditions.It studies in a comparative way the reception of identifiably “canonical” and of extra-canonical traditions in the second century. It aims at discovering patterns or strategies of reception within the at first sight often rather chaotic way some of these ancient authors have cited or used these traditions. And it will look for explanations of why it took such a while before authors got used to cite gospel texts (more or less) accurately.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aApocryphal GospelsvCongresses. 0aGnostic literaturexRelation to the New TestamentvCongresses. 4aEvangelien Tradition. 4aEvangelien. 4aRezeption. 4aZweites Jahrhundert. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Studies / New Testament.2bisacsh  aGospel Traditions.  aGospels.  aReception.  aSecond Century.1 aBazzana, Giovanni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElliott, James Keith, econtributor.4ctb4http